projects: [{'title': 'Move-Based Game Distance (Ludii Games)', 'date': {'start': {'month': 2, 'day': None, 'year': 2021}, 'end': {'month': 6, 'day': None, 'year': 2021}}, 'description': 'This project involving measuring the similarity between various games according to a common property all games have, the moves during play. The main objective of this project is to determine whether a distance metric based purely on the types of moves made during two games is possible and to implement said metric. During several experiments, it was discovered that to make the metric reliable, it is not enough to compare just the types of the moves. This is because several games share the same move types but are still far from being the same. Therefore improvements were made to the implementation, such as incorporating elements from game descriptions in the form of game concepts which resulted in a more robust metric.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Dimitrios', 'last_name': 'Gagatsis', 'name': None, 'headline': 'MSc Data Science | BSc Mathematics'}]}, {'title': 'Repeated Games with Forced Repeated Action Pairs', 'date': {'start': {'month': 9, 'day': None, 'year': 2020}, 'end': {'month': 1, 'day': None, 'year': 2021}}, 'description': "Repeated games are a popular area of study within Game Theory, however, little research has been done on the effect of forcing players to repeat the same action once or multiple times. The goal of this paper is to investigate the effect of forced repeated action pairs on the outcome of a repeated game. To tackle this task, well-known repeated games, such as the prisoner's dilemma and the matching pennies game, are studied in an attempt to discover the effect of forced repeated action pairs on their equilibrium. Further, the economic phenomenon, known as the Bullwhip effect, is modelled and investigated as a repeated game to discover the changes to the Bullwhip effect that forced repeated action pairs can cause. The paper will begin with a brief explanation of repeated games and the idea of forced repeated action pairs. This is followed by theoretical analysis on zero-sum repeated games, the prisoner's dilemma, and the Bullwhip effect. The simulation created to experiment with forced repeated action pairs is then explained, followed by an outline of the experiments performed. Results and discussion follow, and the paper is then concluded.", 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Dimitrios', 'last_name': 'Gagatsis', 'name': None, 'headline': 'MSc Data Science | BSc Mathematics'}]}]
